Busy Beaver and Sneaky Snake visit a carrot shop. There are N carrots for sale, arranged in a row from left to right. The carrots are numbered 1, 2, ..., N from left to right, and the i-th carrot has a flavor index a_i.
They want to eat carrots to maximize their total satisfaction. They take turns eating carrots, with Busy Beaver going first.

On Busy Beaver's turn, he eats one of the two leftmost remaining carrots.
On Sneaky Snake's turn, she eats one of the two rightmost remaining carrots.
If only one carrot remains, the player whose turn it is must eat it.

When a player eats a carrot, they gain satisfaction equal to that carrot's flavor index. The game ends when all carrots have been eaten.
Both players play optimally to maximize their own total satisfaction. Before they start, Busy Beaver wants to know the final total satisfactions of Busy Beaver and Sneaky Snake.
Furthermore, the shop owner frequently changes the flavor index of a carrot. There are Q modifications; in each modification, the flavor index of one carrot is changed. After each modification, compute the final total satisfactions of both players. Note that the modifications are applied cumulatively.

Input Format:
The first line contains a single integer T (1 <= T <= 10^4) — the number of test cases.
The first line of each test case contains two integers N and Q (4 <= N <= 2 * 10^5, 0 <= Q <= 2 * 10^5).
The second line of each test case contains N integers a_1, a_2, ..., a_N, where a_i is the initial flavor index of the i-th carrot (1 <= a_i <= 10^9).
Each of the next Q lines contains two integers x_i and v_i, meaning that in the i-th modification, the flavor index of the x_i-th carrot is changed to v_i (1 <= x_i <= N, 1 <= v_i <= 10^9).
The sum of N across all test cases does not exceed 2 * 10^5.
The sum of Q across all test cases does not exceed 2 * 10^5.

Output Format:
For each test case, output Q + 1 lines.
On the first line, output the final total satisfactions of Busy Beaver and Sneaky Snake respectively for the initial flavor indices.
On the next Q lines, in the i-th line, output the final total satisfactions after applying the first i modifications.

Strategy:
I have solved this problem only for 40 points (N<=5 || Q=0). I did get it in the last 20 minutes though. Submitted a minute before the end. The logic was pretty simple when there weren't size constraints. I just simulated it. The rules are clear, we put the carrots in a deque and for each turn we remove the biggest carrot from the 2 at the front and another biggest from the 2 at the back. We add the values to the totals of the 2 participants until we reach the end. Since I didn't care about constraints, I just made a copy of the deque at the start of each modification (including no mods) and just redid the whole process, at the end i loaded in the new modification to the master array from which I made copies. There were a few edge cases, since I was doing the modifications at the end I needed to break when i==q since there were no mods for that and I also needed to break after the first animals turn if the size of the carrot array was 0 and also not check 2 carrots if there was only one left. Other than that it was pretty straightforward to get the 40 points.
Now for the upsolving I did after the contest. The key to get the full points was finding a formula for the amount of points the animal will get and then just augmenting it. The required realization is that the array for 2 animals is essentially 2 arrays, one for each, since they have their own side they don't overlap and the only moment where we need to combine them is at the last turn when there is only <=2 total carrots left. Since the animal will always choose a bigger from 2, it will just continuously be eating up its subarray until there is only 1 carrot left, since it always took the bigger one this most be the minimum in the array. At that point, the first animal will take the bigger one and the second will take the smaller one. This is constrained by there being a total even amount of carrots so that they both are left with 1 carrot for the last turn. For this, the formula is sumOfSubarray-min(subarray) and then for the animal that started the game we add max(min1,min2) and for the second one, the smallest carrot is left. For an odd amount of carrots, we need to give the starting animal the bigger subarray, then we iterate like normal but at the end there will be 3 carrots. Since the first animal started and there was an odd amount of turns it will also end, the last carrot will always be the smallest one since no-one would pick it. Therefore the first animal will get the absolute smallest carrot. The equation for odd numbers is therefore max(min1,min2) for the second animal and min(min1,min2) for the first one, needless to say the first animal still probably gets more since it got one extra carrot (its subarray was 1 bigger). This process is a self-contained way to calculate the points. Now for the modifications, the smart trick is to put the the carrots in 2 multisets (RBTs) and with a precalculated sum (we do that when loading the carrots in) we always just look at the root of the tree for the smallest element in each subarray. The mods become easy since we just do sum-=carrots[changedIdx]; sum+=newNumber. We do need to keep an array with the carrots accessible by the original indices so we know what the mod instructions mean, then we always just retrieve the number and find it in one of the subarrays, after that we also update the array with indices to have the correct value. For the multiset we just do ms.erase(ms.find(arr[idx])) and then ms.insert(newNum) for the ms we identified as the one that had the number (we do that by using the idx obtained from arr and comparing to the middle (n/2), if it is smaller the number is in the left multiset.) For each modification we just repeat this augmentation process and output the points. Also, small important thing, we need to convert the indices in the modification vector to 0 indexed since we get them as 1 indexed. Therefore, we either decrease the numbers at the start or use (n+1)/2 and do -1 in places where accessing the index.